So since this place seems to be blowing up, is Discord still the right medium for this community? I was thinking the longer discussions could go on a forum or message board hosted on the Gen Z Mafia domain. That way, it could keep Discord clear for chatting while better preserving the deep convos for people to read later (and also get indexed by search engines and stuff).

I personally wouldn’t want my chat messages even on more serious convos to be archived or indexed. I prefer the closed door approach even if the door is just logging into a discord server. It’s sad that some likely valuable discourse will be lost, but that’s a price I’m willing to pay in order to be able to speak without worrying too much about the ramifications of having my real identity attached to what I say.
A big thing about this community is that we wanna keep it exclusive to those who are in it. By all means we allow anyone to join but the content and perks inside it stays in

Then maybe an invite only wiki or something? Like maybe even charge a subscription fee (like how people have Patreon tiers)? I'm just thinking that telling people to "lurk moar" isn't a scalable way to grant access to our knowledge. It just makes the same questions repeat again and again in chat.
i think an invite only wiki would be interesting but as the others have said i feel like discord is a fleeting-msg & in-the-moment type of platform

I think a invite only wiki for archiving and sharing notes would be good, and maybe a discord bot using Notion's eventual API to add stuff to a "triage" page so you can add links to it over time would be great.

My original question was:

> Something I wanted to ask at the Q&A that I think is important - can we stop using the terms "Daddy" and "Sugar Daddy".
> 
> 1) These terms are gendered. We would never call them "Mommas" for example.
> 2) "Daddy" has strong sexual undertones.
> 3) In the "Sugar Daddy" metaphor, doesn't that make us all "Prostitutes"?
After getting responses that indicated people felt like there wasn't much wrong with these terms, I sent a few female friends the following message:

> Hey X. Can you help me out with something? I've been participating in a discord channel for gen Zers, primarily those in tech, for the past few days. One thing they do that I dislike is some of the terms they use and I'm pushing to change them. They use the term "Daddy" to describe anyone that's older than a gen Zer and they use the term "Sugar Daddy" to describe a VC. Since I'm not a woman, I wanted to ask a few women and get their opinion on it, which I'll then present as evidence for whether or not the terms should be changed.

> 1) As a woman, do you find the terms "Daddy" and "Sugar Daddy" to be welcoming?
> 2) Elaborate. What are you opinions on the usage of the terms "Daddy" and "Sugar Daddy"?
And I got the following responses:

> 1) No and Hell no.
> 2) Daddy is uncomfortably immature and/or sexual for anyone over age ten. (Mommy is also immature, but without the sexual overtones.) Sugar Daddy is just explicitly sexual, and it implies to me that women are capable for solely their appearance and sexuality, while men are valuable solely for their money. There's some more underlying implications that women only care about money and men only care about sex (with young, vulnerable women) that are also pretty demeaning.
> 
> Also, are all Millennials-and-older and all VCs male? Given that it's tech, I suspect they're heavily skewed male and terminology like "Daddy" exacerbates that problem
> 
> I very much support your efforts to change those phrases

#2
> I don’t find them welcoming. I wouldn’t say they are unwelcoming exactly, but certainly distasteful and immature. I’d limit my participation in a discord like that or maybe leave, but idk maybe the value of the discord outweighs the distaste in some parts.

#3 
> Ya actually swapping VCs to be wallets instead of a daddy or sugar daddy would be gender neutral and better for everyone
> 
> We should call non gen z “fossils” instead of daddy as
> 
> ANYWAYS. Those terms are not appropriate and not welcoming but tbh that could be their intent.
So 3/3 women have expressed that they feel those phrases are inappropriate and that they wouldn't feel welcome here.
